.\" Manpage for _printf project functions
.\" Description: Custom printf implementation with helper functions
.\" Author: [Amaal Asiri / Mostafa Alalmi]

.TH _PRINTF_PROJECT 3 "2025" "1.0" "Custom Printf Implementation"

.SH NAME
_printf, _putchar, print_string, print_number \- formatted output conversion and helper functions

.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
.B #include "main.h"
.PP
.BI "int _printf(const char *" format ", ...);"
.BI "int _putchar(char " c ");"
.BI "int print_string(char *" str ");"
.BI "int print_number(int " n ");"
.fi

.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf
function produces output according to a
.I format
string and writes it to
.BR stdout ,
the standard output stream.

The
.I format
string is a character string composed of zero or more directives:
.IP \(bu 2
Ordinary characters (not
.BR % ),
which are copied unchanged to the output stream.
.IP \(bu 2
Conversion specifications, each of which results in fetching zero or more
subsequent arguments. Each conversion specification is introduced by the
.B %
character and ends with a conversion specifier.

.SS Helper Functions
.TP
.B _putchar()
Writes a single character to stdout.

.TP
.B print_string()
Prints a string of characters. If the string is NULL, prints "(null)".

.TP
.B print_number()
Prints a signed decimal integer, handling both positive and negative numbers.

.SH CONVERSION SPECIFIERS
The following conversion specifiers are supported:

.TP
.B %c
Prints a single character.

.TP
.B %s
Prints a string of characters.

.TP
.B %%
Prints a literal % character.

.TP
.B %d, %i
Prints a signed decimal integer.

.PP
The
.B _printf
function does not handle flag characters, field width, precision, or length modifiers.

.SH RETURN VALUE
Upon successful return, all functions return the number of characters printed 
(excluding the null byte used to end output to strings).

If an output error is encountered, a negative value is returned.

.SH EXAMPLES
The following example demonstrates the use of all functions:

.nf
#include "main.h"

int main(void)
{
    int len;
    
    /* Using _printf with various specifiers */
    len = _printf("Hello, %s!\\n", "world");
    _printf("Printed %d characters\\\\n", len);
    _printf("Character: %c, Number: %d\\\\n", 'A', 42);
    _printf("Percent sign: %%\\\\n");
    _printf("Negative: %i\\\\n", -123);
    
    /* Using helper functions directly */
    _putchar('H');
    _putchar('i');
    _putchar('\\\\n');
    
    print_string("Direct string print\\\\n");
    print_number(999);
    _putchar('\\\\n');
    
    return (0);
}
.fi

.SH COMPILATION
Compile your code with:
.nf
.B gcc -Wall -Werror -Wextra -pedantic -std=gnu89 -Wno-format *.c
.fi

.SH AUTHORED FUNCTIONS
The implementation uses the following authorized functions and macros:
.IP \(bu 2
.BR write (2)
.IP \(bu 2
.BR malloc (3)
.IP \(bu 2
.BR free (3)
.IP \(bu 2
.BR va_start (3)
.IP \(bu 2
.BR va_end (3)
.IP \(bu 2
.BR va_copy (3)
.IP \(bu 2
.BR va_arg (3)

.SH PROJECT STRUCTURE
.nf
main.h          - Header file with function prototypes
_printf.c       - Main _printf function implementation
_putchar.c      - Helper functions (_putchar, print_string, print_number)
README.md       - Project documentation
.fi

.SH IMPLEMENTATION DETAILS
.IP \(bu 2
Uses variadic functions for handling variable arguments
.IP \(bu 2
Implements recursion for integer printing
.IP \(bu 2
Handles NULL strings gracefully by printing "(null)"
.IP \(bu 2
Follows Betty coding style standards
.IP \(bu 2
Compiles with strict warning flags

.SH BUGS
The
.B _printf
function is a custom implementation and may not handle all edge cases exactly like the standard
.BR printf (3)
function.

This implementation does not handle buffer management like the C library printf function.

The following features are not implemented:
.IP \(bu 2
Flag characters (+, space, #, 0, -)
.IP \(bu 2
Field width
.IP \(bu 2
Precision
.IP \(bu 2
Length modifiers (h, l, L)
.IP \(bu 2
Other conversion specifiers (u, o, x, X, p, etc.)

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR printf (3),
.BR write (2),
.BR stdarg (3),
.BR putchar (3)

.SH STANDARDS
This implementation follows the GNU89 standard and Betty coding style.

.SH HISTORY
This custom _printf implementation was developed as part of the Holberton School curriculum to understand variadic functions and the inner workings of printf.

.SH AUTHORS
Amaal Asiri and Mostafa Alalmi as part of a Holberton School group project.
